                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/442.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Mexican Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexican Embassy</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington,
                                D. C.</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <lb/> [<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-20">undated</date>] (Received April
                        20, 1912—1.30 p.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With reference to the note of this Embassy No. 1229 of 30th March,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d1077fn1">Not printed.</note> your note 155, 6th April,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d1077fn2">Not printed.</note> and further correspondence relative to
                    the exportation to Mexico of war materials detained at Marfa, Texas, I have the
                    honor to inform you that the Consul of Mexico at El Paso has informed me that
                    Marshal Nolte, who is detaining said materials, says permission of the
                    Department of Justice is required in order to release said materials. Therefore
                    I request that you be pleased to direct what is necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilberto Crespo y Martinez</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
